<section aria-label="Glossary terms coming soon" style="margin-top: 32px;">
  <h2 style="font-size: 22px; color: var(--ink); margin-bottom: 12px;">Coming soon</h2>
  <div class="section-grid">
    <div class="section-card stub">
      <span class="coming-soon-tag">Coming soon</span>
      <div class="card-title">Subduction</div>
      <div class="card-desc">When one tectonic plate dives beneath another. The setup for the largest earthquakes and tsunamis on Earth.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card stub">
      <span class="coming-soon-tag">Coming soon</span>
      <div class="card-title">Megathrust</div>
      <div class="card-desc">The biggest kind of earthquake — a sudden slip on the interface between subducting plates. M9+.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card stub">
      <span class="coming-soon-tag">Coming soon</span>
      <div class="card-title">Pyroclastic flow</div>
      <div class="card-desc">A fast-moving cloud of superheated gas and rock from a volcanic eruption. No engineering defense — only distance and warning save lives.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card stub">
      <span class="coming-soon-tag">Coming soon</span>
      <div class="card-title">Lahar</div>
      <div class="card-desc">A volcanic mudflow — ash + water moving like wet concrete down valleys. Can destroy villages years after the eruption.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card stub">
      <span class="coming-soon-tag">Coming soon</span>
      <div class="card-title">Magnitude vs. intensity</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Two different things people confuse: how much energy the quake released (magnitude) vs. how strongly the ground shook somewhere (intensity).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card stub">
      <span class="coming-soon-tag">Coming soon</span>
      <div class="card-title">Volcanic Explosivity Index (VEI)</div>
      <div class="card-desc">The 0–8 logarithmic scale for ranking eruption size. Pinatubo 1991 was VEI 6.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card stub">
      <span class="coming-soon-tag">Coming soon</span>
      <div class="card-title">Lithosphere / asthenosphere</div>
      <div class="card-desc">The rigid outer shell of Earth that's broken into plates (lithosphere) and the slowly-flowing layer beneath (asthenosphere) that they move on.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card stub">
      <span class="coming-soon-tag">Coming soon</span>
      <div class="card-title">Transform fault</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Where two plates slide horizontally past each other. Big shaking, no tsunami. Examples: San Andreas, Anatolian.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card stub">
      <span class="coming-soon-tag">Coming soon</span>
      <div class="card-title">Hotspot</div>
      <div class="card-desc">A plume of mantle material that punches through a plate from below — Hawaii's source. Mostly produces effusive shield volcanoes, not catastrophic eruptions.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
